utterances.speaker: C
utterances.text: Counselors meet with and work with a whole range of people. Some present difficult situations which they are keen to talk about to someone who will listen to them and understand what they are going through. Counseling can be relatively straightforward, even though it may be full of pain and difficulty for the client. Others, for one reason or another, make the actual interview or parts of the interview difficult for the counselor, perhaps ultimately because they are finding the situation very difficult themselves. But it is not always easy at the time for a counselor to be so understanding of the awkward situation. We have to respond in some way to the request, the protest, or the information the client drops on us. Sometimes we respond well, sometimes not so well, and there are always those times when afterwards you say to yourself, if only I had said this, or if only I had said that. In this series of vignettes, we play out the role of counselor and client in a number of awkward situations which we have come across in our practice. In every case, we try initially to make a response which is helpful, although it is probably not the most helpful response that could be given. So each scene is shown twice. The video is best stopped after the first shot of each scene for you to discuss what you think about the first response given and how else you might respond. The scene is then shown a second time, but with an alternative response by the counselor, one which, at least in our opinion, is better than the first. There is, of course, never just one correct way to respond to an awkward situation. But we think the second response is careful, as indeed the first may be, but also gets hold of the underlying issue which the client is trying to express. You too, in your discussions between the two versions, will come up with equally valid alternatives which fully acknowledge the situation which the client brings or creates.
